# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: supabase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Web and mobile apps require a similar set of features on the backend, including notification service, integration with social networks, and cloud storage.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Each of these services has its own API that must be individually incorporated into an app, a process that can be time-consuming and complicated for app developers.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers form a bridge between the frontend of an application and various cloud-based backends via a unified API and SDK.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Providing a consistent way to manage backend data means that developers do not need to redevelop their own backend for each of the services that their apps need to access, potentially saving both time and money.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers offer different set of features and backend tools.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers also come in different types, suiting developers of different needs.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Most BaaS providers host backend platforms on their cloud servers.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] They also manage the infrastructure, security, and scalability of the platforms.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Developers can access the backend services via a web interface or the provided APIs.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Some examples of cloud-based BaaS include Firebase (hosted on Google Cloud Platform), AWS Amplify (hosted on Amazon Web Services), and Microsoft Azure Mobile Apps (hosted on Microsoft Azure).
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Self-hosted BaaS allow developers to host backend on their own servers, providing more flexibility and potential to customization compared to cloud-based BaaS, which often is more difficult to migrate from.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] However, developers are also in charge of managing the infrastructure, security, and scalability of their servers.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Mobile backend as a service (MBaaS) is a type of BaaS specifically for applications deployed in mobile systems.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] While some references use MBaaS interchangeably for BaaS, BaaS can have a wider variety of support such as for web apps and desktop apps.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers generate revenue from their services in various ways, often using a freemium model.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Under this model, a client receives a certain number of free active users or API calls per month, and pays a fee for each user or call over this limit.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Alternatively, clients can pay a set fee for a package which allows for a greater number of calls or active users per month.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] There are also flat fee plans that make the pricing more predictable.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Some of the providers offer the unlimited API calls inside their free plan offerings.
[src:supabase/backend-as-a-service] Another business model that has been used by a lot of BaaS providers is PAYG (pay as you go), which has a flexible cost based on developers' usage of database, storage, bandwidth, function calls, user numbers etc.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Supabase is the Postgres development platform.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] We're building the features of Firebase using enterprise-grade open source tools.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Watch "releases" of this repo to get notified of major updates.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Supabase is a combination of open source tools.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] We’re building the features of Firebase using enterprise-grade, open source products.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] If the tools and communities exist, with an MIT, Apache 2, or equivalent open license, we will use and support that tool.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] If the tool doesn't exist, we build and open source it ourselves.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Supabase is not a 1-to-1 mapping of Firebase.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Our aim is to give developers a Firebase-like developer experience using open source tools.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] You can sign up and start using Supabase without installing anything.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] You can also self-host and develop locally.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Our approach for client libraries is modular.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] Each sub-library is a standalone implementation for a single external system.
[src:supabase/blob-readme-md] This is one of the ways we support existing tools.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] A **cloud database** is a database that typically runs on a cloud computing platform, with access provided as a service.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] There are two common deployment models: users can run databases on the cloud independently, using a virtual machine image, or they can purchase access to a database service maintained by a cloud database provider.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Cloud databases may use either a relational SQL or a NoSQL data model.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Database services handle scalability and high availability, while making the underlying software stack transparent to users.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Cloud platforms allow users to purchase virtual machine instances for a limited time, on which a database can be run.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Users can upload their own machine image with a database installed or use ready-made machine images that include an optimized installation of a database.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] With a database as a service (DBaaS) model, users pay a cloud provider for database services and computing resources, which may reduce the operational overhead needed to develop and manage databases.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Users are provided with tools to create and manage database instances, as well as to manage database users.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Some cloud providers also offer tools for managing database structures and data.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] The design and development of typical systems often use data management and relational databases as key building blocks.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Advanced queries expressed in SQL work well with the strict relationships imposed by relational databases.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] However, relational database technology was not originally designed for use over distributed systems.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] This limitation has been addressed through clustering enhancements, although some fundamental operations—such as data synchronization—still require complex and expensive protocols.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Modern relational databases can exhibit poor performance on data-intensive systems.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] As a result, the NoSQL paradigm has been adopted within database management systems for cloud-based systems.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] NoSQL storage does not require fixed table schemas, and join operations are typically avoided.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] NoSQL databases have been shown to provide efficient horizontal scalability, high performance, and ease of integration into cloud applications.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Additionally, data models that rely on simplified relay algorithms have been employed in data-intensive cloud mapping applications specific to virtual frameworks.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] It is also important to differentiate between cloud databases which are relational (SQL) and those that are non-relational (NoSQL).
[src:supabase/cloud-database] SQL databases can run in the cloud either on virtual machines or as a managed service, depending on the vendor.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] While SQL databases are generally easy to scale vertically, horizontal scalability presents a greater challenge.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] making them well suited to cloud environments.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] However, many contemporary applications are built around a relational (SQL) data model, so adopting NoSQL databases often requires significant changes to application code.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] or similar variants), and key-value store data types.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Multi-model databases combine relational and non-relational capabilities, providing a standard SQL interface to users and applications.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] Native multi-model databases support multiple data models with a single core, facilitating their use in applications built around SQL.
[src:supabase/cloud-database] The following table lists notable database vendors that offer cloud database services, classified by deployment model—machine image or database as a service—and by data model (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:supabase/database-overview] Use Supabase to connect, manage, and secure your Postgres database.
[src:supabase/database-overview] Every Supabase project gets a full Postgres database, not a Postgres abstraction.
[src:supabase/database-overview] This database is the foundation that Auth, Storage, Realtime, and Edge Functions are built on, and Supabase manages daily database backups and offers point-in-time recovery on paid plans.
[src:supabase/guides-api] Supabase auto-generates an API directly from your database schema allowing you to connect to your database through a restful interface, directly from the browser.
[src:supabase/guides-api] The API is auto-generated from your database and is designed to get you building as fast as possible, without writing a single line of code.
[src:supabase/guides-api] You can use them directly from the browser (two-tier architecture), or as a complement to your own API server (three-tier architecture).
[src:supabase/guides-api] Supabase provides a RESTful API using PostgREST, a thin API layer on top of Postgres.
[src:supabase/guides-api] It exposes everything you need from a CRUD API at the URL `https://<project_ref>.supabase.co/rest/v1/`.
[src:supabase/guides-api] The REST API resolves all requests to a single SQL statement leading to fast response times and high throughput.
[src:supabase/page] Learn how to get up and running with Supabase through tutorials, APIs and platform resources.
[src:supabase/page] Set up and connect a database in just a few minutes.
[src:supabase/page] Bring your existing data, auth and storage to Supabase following our migration guides.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:supabase/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:supabase/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:supabase/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:supabase/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:supabase/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:supabase/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:supabase/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:supabase/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:supabase/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:supabase/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:supabase/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:supabase/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:supabase/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:supabase/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:supabase/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:supabase/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:supabase/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:supabase/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:supabase/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:supabase/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:supabase/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:supabase/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:supabase/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:supabase/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:supabase/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:supabase/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:supabase/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:supabase/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:supabase/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:supabase/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:supabase/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:supabase/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:supabase/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:supabase/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:supabase/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:supabase/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:supabase/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:supabase/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:supabase/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:supabase/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:supabase/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:supabase/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:supabase/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:supabase/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:supabase/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:supabase/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:supabase/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:supabase/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:supabase/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:supabase/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:supabase/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:supabase/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:supabase/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:supabase/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:supabase/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:supabase/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:supabase/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:supabase/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:supabase/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:supabase/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:supabase/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:supabase/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:supabase/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:supabase/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:supabase/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:supabase/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:supabase/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:supabase/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:supabase/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:supabase/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:supabase/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:supabase/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:supabase/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:supabase/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:supabase/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:supabase/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:supabase/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:supabase/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:supabase/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:supabase/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:supabase/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:supabase/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:supabase/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:supabase/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:supabase/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:supabase/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:supabase/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:supabase/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:supabase/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:supabase/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:supabase/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:supabase/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
